  "explanation": [
    {
      "heading": "HashMap Internals",
      "body": "Under the hood, a HashMap is an array of **buckets**.\n\n`put(key, val)` computes `index = hash(key) % array_size` and stores the entry at that index.",
      "appearsAtStep": 0
    },
    {
      "heading": "Hash Function",
      "body": "A good hash function:\n- Distributes keys **uniformly** across buckets\n- Is **fast** to compute (O(1))\n- Produces the **same index** for equal keys\n\nJava's `hashCode()` and Python's `hash()` XOR the bits of the key representation.",
      "appearsAtStep": 1,
      "callout": "Bad hash function → all keys land in same bucket → O(n) performance."
    },
    {
      "heading": "Collision → Chaining",
      "body": "Two different keys can hash to the same bucket — this is a **collision**.\n\n**Chaining**: each bucket holds a **linked list** of all entries that map there.\n\nLookup: hash(key) → find bucket → scan the chain for matching key.\n\nAverage case: O(1) if load factor is low.",
      "appearsAtStep": 3
    },
    {
      "heading": "Load Factor & Resizing",
      "body": "Load factor = `entries / bucket_count`.\n\nWhen load factor exceeds **0.75** (threshold used by Java's HashMap):\n1. Allocate a new array 2× the size\n2. **Rehash** all entries into new buckets\n\nThis keeps average chain length close to 1, maintaining O(1) lookups.",
      "appearsAtStep": 6,
      "callout": "Resize is O(n), but amortized over n insertions it's still O(1) average per put()."
    }
  ],

